<div id="p49" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#7&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=49#p49">2008-03-05 00:29:51</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89601">dave</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Editor</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEPs 17 and 19: HTTP Seeding.</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>Michael,<br /><br />I would prefer that the BEP clearly separate what is standardizable from what are recommendations.&nbsp; There are some sentences that use the word &quot;must&quot; but occur in the implementation sections.<br /><br />I would prefer IETF RFC 2119 style usage of words like SHOULD, MUST, and RECOMMEND to clarify what is expected of client developers. <br /><br />One way to make the BEP more easily accepted is to separate it into a short standards track BEP that only presents the metainfo extensions and then refer to a lengthier informational BEP in which you describe all of the potential client implementations.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
