<div id="p65" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#11&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=65#p65">2008-03-05 17:52:00</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89624">dak360</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"><img src="img/avatars/89624.jpg" width="64" height="64" alt="" /></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEPs 17 and 19: HTTP Seeding.</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>As someone who runs a tracker and a tornado spec web seed, I would have to say that I prefer it for a number of reasons.<br /><br />One is that it allows me to easily restrict downloading of the files to persons using a bittorrent client.<br /><br />Another is that it lets me set the rate of transfer for just those files without having to mess with the rest of my webserver; indeed if it were not my server in the first place I might very well not be able to add mod_* if the service did not already have it.<br /><br />Finally, ideally the web seed would be a part of the tracker and would only seed when needed (or according to whatever rules you define), along with other refinements (like not needing any additional setup beyond telling it where the files are).</p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />- dak180<br /><a href="http://dak180.dynalias.com:8080/PHP/tracker/" rel="nofollow">BaenCD Torrents</a></div>
			</div>
