<div id="p307" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#14&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=307#p307">2008-07-30 20:01:02</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89879">herman</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEPs 17 and 19: HTTP Seeding.</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>&gt; Web servers don't really like random requests for 16 kbytes.<br /><br />Deluge and libTorrent have a nasty habit of requesting 16 kB pieces. The web server logs are constantly written to while multiple GET requests are being processed. Certainly even a low-end dedicated server can handle 150GB via web seed in one day (14.2 megabit per second). But I fear clients like Deluge and libTorrent will cause unreasonable load on hosting accounts that are shared.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
